post_text: FPS is pleased to announce that Ed Clapp, Madison and Jefferson will participate in a free breakfast and lunch program for the 2020-2021 school year. This program is referred to as the Community Eligibility Provision (CEP). CEP is a four-year reimbursement option for eligible schools participating in both the National School Lunch Program and School Breakfast Program that wish to offer free meals to all students in a school with a high prevalence of low-income families without collecting free and reduced meal applications. For additional information: https://www.fargo.k12.nd.us/Page/2136

post_text: Need a good book? The last summer book pick up is August 5 and we need your book preferences. Student can check out, pick up, and return books. Begin by filling out the form telling librarians the type of books they would like; this will be done each time you wish to check out books, with a limit of five books per check out. Then pick up their books during the pickup time window, return their books on the next available date, and request more. Those who check out books on the final date will return the books to school once school is back in session. Book request form: http://ow.ly/a00730qIfZk

post_text: Fargo Public Schools announces the assignment of the Director of Equity and Inclusion, a new position for the District. The Director of Equity and Inclusion develops, implements, administers, and monitors a variety of programs focused on diversity, equity, and inclusion for Fargo Public Schools (FPS). Additionally, the Director of Equity and Inclusion provides leadership and guidance to all FPS employees in the effort to advocate for diversity, equity, and intercultural competency as part of the Districtâ€™s endeavors to create an education environment of inclusiveness, equity, and respect for all people. post_text: The generosity & creativity of Mrs Meline's Kindergartners from Eagles is so heartwarming. Since the class didn't get to do their annual spring visit to Touchmark Senior Living due to Covid, a student in class (and her mom) wrote a community outreach grant to fund a flower delivery project! Each Kindergartner colored & decorated papers to wrap around flower containers, at their own homes & mailed them back to their teacher. Lydia helped get fresh flowers ready. They delivered 60 bouquets to Touchmark Senior Living so the students could spread a little cheer to the residents. #FPSproud

Congratulations to the students who participated and placed in the 2020 Scholastic Art & Writing Awards.

Olivia Drake, junior at Davies High School, received a Gold Key award at the National Level for her short story Freedom Lives, which was inspired by the bombing of the 16th Street Baptist Church in Birmingham, Alabama in 1963.

Olivia Propeck, senior at Davies High School, received a National Gold Key award and "Best-in-Grade" for her piece titled Jamaica, a Regional Silver Key award and NDSU Arts Department scholarship for her piece I'm Fine, and a Silver Key award for her piece Montego Bay.

post_text:
Congratulations to two students from North who received recognition during the National History Day (NHD) Competition!

Junior Jordan Garske took First Place for his paper titled "Breaking Barriers: Cracking the Code of DNA's Structure and Advances in Genetic Research." He is now eligible to compete in the National Competition in June.
Junior Lexie Schwarz received a $150 award for her paper titled "U.S. Women's Soccer Making Changes."

The National History Day Contest encourages students around the world to conduct historical research on a topic of their choice. Students enter these projects at the local and affiliate levels, with top students advancing to the National Contest at the University of Maryland at College Park.

post_text: This week is North Dakota Severe Weather Awareness Week! At FPS we do various emergency drills monthly. Our drill practices have been recently disrupted by COVID-19 at school, but we encourage families to practice their emergency procedures at home. To honor Severe Weather Awareness Week, Cass County will be sounding the tornado sirens throughout the county on Wednesday, April 29 at 11:15 a.m. When you hear the alarms, take time to practice your emergency plans at home. For more resources and information on severe weather safety check out ready.gov. #FPSproud #SafetyFirst

post_text: Talk about delicious! Fargo Public Schools Nutrition Services will start to include additional servings of fresh fruits and vegetables in their meal distribution through the Fresh Fruit and Vegetable Program (FFVP). This grant program is funded through the U.S. Department of Agriculture and provides a variety of free fresh fruits and vegetables to children throughout the school year. post_text: Tonight, the FPS high schools joined the #Bethelight movement with other schools from across the country by turning on their stadium lights for 20 minutes and 20 seconds. The movement started to show support of students, schools, and communities with a sign of hope. The stadium lights were on from 8:00-8:20 p.m. to let the students and community know that we will be back to normal with events in stadiums, gyms, theaters, fields, courses, and on ice at some point. For now, we need to support one another by following guidelines given by local, state, and federal authorities in hopes of slowing the spread of COVID-19.

In the last few days, teachers and librarians have produced hundreds of videos for students to access to compliment the elementary Learning Boards that will be used during distance learning. iPads are being imaged with resources, including 532 videos, for families that do not have technology or internet access at home. The iPads will be distributed by schools the week of March 30 to families who have made contact with the building principal or a childâ€™s teacher. All resources are also available online via each schoolâ€™s website for families with their own devices and access to the internet. iPad imaging is being completed with health and safety at the forefront; all machines are being disinfected and staff members are wearing gloves when handling devices.

post_text: 5th graders from Kennedy began taking ukulele lessons. Students learned to tune, strum, and play along with a few songs. post_text: In September of 2019, the North Dakota Department of Public Instruction (NDDPI) was notified it had been selected for an award of funds from the U.S. Department of Education for the Comprehensive State Literacy Development (CSLD) grant over the course of five years. The goal of the CSLD grant program is to improve the reading and writing of young children and students. With CSLD funds, NDDPI has designed a coaching support model, with planned training to provide educators with comprehensive literacy instructional strategies. In February, the District applied for the funds made available to local education agencies through a competitive grant process. https://bit.ly/39O07aO

post_text: Congratulations to Fargo Public Schools Visual Arts Instructor Chelsea Odden on recently having her article titled "Rethinking Reflection Practices: Using Social Topics to Expand Meaning-Making" published in the March 2020 Issue of The Journal of the National Art Education Association. This article is based on her research during graduate school at the Maryland Institute College of Art. Odden's research looked at the effects of providing strategies on making personally meaningful artwork. https://bit.ly/3d37Sf0

post_text: Ms. Roth's seventh period Spanish students at Carl Ben Eielson Middle School had a visit from Martin E. Echegaray Davies, an Argentinean who has a goal of walking from Argentina to Alaska in less than three years. Martin left his home on October 31, 2017. He spent an unplanned month and a half in Fargo waiting out the weather. Martin told stories from his travels and shared pictures from his journey, along with answering questions from the students. Martin does not speak English, so all of this was shared in Spanish with Ms. Roth translating. #FPSlearns

Due to the projected weather forecast and blizzard conditions, all classes and extra-curricular activities are cancelled for students of the Fargo Public Schools for Wednesday, February 12, including the Early Childhood Special Education pre-school and Adult Learning Center. Students are not to report to school; staff members are not to report to work.

Due to the cancellation, Fargo Public Schools will use a storm make up day that is built into the school calendar. Fargo Public Schools will hold classes on Monday, April 13, 2020; this is now a day that students and staff are expected to be at school.

Congratulations to the five winners from the Clara Barton Spelling Bee for 2020. After spelling a total of 188 words, the following students have been crowned winners:
1st Place - Nate Wilson, fourth grade
2nd Place - Hannah Wiltse, fourth grade
3rd Place - Nyah Romaine, fifth grade
4th Place - Jack Shea, fifth grade
5th Place - Addy Johnson, fifth grade
The students will move on to the Cass County Spelling Bee held on Tuesday, February 25 at the El Zagel Shrine.

post_text: Congrats to all three Fargo high school dance teams who competed in the North Dakota Association of Dance and Drill State Competition. The teams made history by each qualifying for finals in the state Jazz category for the first time: North Spartacas placed 3rd in Class A Small Varsity Pom & 4th in Small Varsity Jazz; South Bruinkix are State Champs in Class A Small Varsity Jazz, 2nd in Small Varsity Pom & 2nd in Small Varsity High Kick; Davies Eagles Elite are State Champs in Class A Large Varsity Jazz, 2nd in Large Varsity Hip Hop, 2nd in Large Varsity Pom, & Third in Large Varsity High Kick.
text: Congrats to all three Fargo high school dance teams who competed in the North Dakota Association of Dance and Drill State Competition. Students spent five minutes in three separate areas choosing genres and completing a â€œbook menuâ€ form after previewing covers and reading summaries. post_text: Carl Ben Eielson's production of Elf Jr. The Musical opens TONIGHT 7:30 p.m. in the South High School theater - enter on 17th Ave. S. Additional performances are Friday, January 24 at 7:30 p.m., and Saturday, January 25 at 2:00 p.m. at South High School. Admission is free with general seating. It is the tale of Buddy, a young orphan who mistakenly crawls into Santa's bag of gifts and is transported to the North Pole. Buddy then embarks on a journey to New York City to find his birth father and discover his true identity. Faced with the harsh reality that his father is on the naughty list and his stepbrother doesnâ€™t even believe in Santa, Buddy is determined to win over his new family and help New York remember the true meaning of Christmas.

ATTENTION! Due to forecasted winter weather, Fargo Public Schools will dismiss school early today, Friday, January 17, 2020. Due to bussing schedules, a staggered dismissal will be as follows:

â€¢ Clara Barton Elementary and Roosevelt Elementary will dismiss at 10:50 a.m.
â€¢ All other elementary schools will dismiss at 11:00 a.m., including the Early Childhood Special Education program. The afternoon Early Childhood Special Education program is cancelled. After school child care programs are cancelled.
â€¢ All middle schools and high schools will dismiss at 11:45 a.m.

All after-school activities are canceled for Friday, January 17.

Elementary schools will follow the directions for student pickup per parent direction on the school closure information form completed at registration. Essential personnel will remain at the buildings until all students have been picked up.

In addition, all buildings will be closed, and all activities are cancelled on Saturday, January 18, 2020.
